				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Mumbai&#8217;s Business Community Tries New Enterprise: Politics</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Mansi Choksi			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-04-21T13:26:16+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">April 21, 2014 9:26 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">April 21, 2014 9:26 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/21/world/asia/21-walker-indiaink/21-walker-indiaink-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/21/world/asia/21-walker-indiaink/21-walker-indiaink-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/21/world/asia/21-walker-indiaink/21-walker-indiaink-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002836351" width="592" height="372" alt="Arvind Sawant, center, the Shiv Sena candidate from South Mumbai, interacting with morning walkers at Priyadarshini park in Mumbai, Maharashtra, on Monday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="372"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Arvind Sawant, center, the Shiv Sena candidate from South Mumbai, interacting with morning walkers at Priyadarshini park in Mumbai, Maharashtra, on Monday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Mansi Choksi</span></figcaption></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/mumbais-business-community-tries-new-enterprise-politics/" data-title="Mumbai&#8217;s Business Community Tries New Enterprise: Politics" data-description="Members of the white-collar elite who have shunned participating in past campaigns are now motivated to stump for Narendra Modi of the Bharatiya Janata Party. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">MUMBAI &#8212; At Priyadarshini Park in the Malabar Hill neighborhood of south Mumbai, under the shade of neatly aligned coconut trees, a platoon of middle-aged stock brokers discussed the volatility of the Indian stock markets as they went on their regular power walk along the frothy shoreline of the Arabian Sea.</p>
<div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><h6 class="kicker"><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/category/india-votes/">India Votes</a></h6><p class="summary">News and analysis on the worldâs largest election. </p></div></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">An acquaintance, wearing a T-shirt that read âR U Ready 2 Vote,â introduced them to Arvind Sawant, the Shiv Senaâs local parliamentary candidate, who extended his hand to the group. âVote for the bow-and-arrow symbol to elect Modi<i>ji</i>,â Mr. Sawant said, referring to Narendra Modi of the main opposition Bharatiya Janata Party. âOur party has built 55 flyovers, and we will build more.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Sawant, 62, a former trade union leader at MTNL, the state-owned telephone service provider, was raised in a middle-class family in Sewri, an industrial neighborhood in a neglected corner of his constituency. Today, he is on the speed-dial lists of a number of Mumbai&#8217;s power brokers who have come together to lobby for the National Democratic Alliance, the center-right coalition led by the B.J.P., which has a Maharashtra State ally in the Hindu nationalist Shiv Sena party.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These privileged Indians, who call themselves âIndia Firstâ â entrepreneurs, investment bankers, hoteliers â are products of the countryâs liberalized economy, graduates of Ivy League schools and employees of global corporations. As a group, they are âprogressive, like-minded Indiansâ who believe that only Mr. Modi, the B.J.P. candidate for prime minister, can bail India out.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhether it is economic development, administration or good governance, he is head and shoulders above any other option available,â said Akshay Jalan, 32, an entrepreneur with several businesses, including some related to hedge funds.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Indiaâs white-collar elite has traditionally been known to avoid engaging publicly, relying largely on the private sector for transport, education, water and security. But the consequences of massive corruption scandals, a tumbling currency, stalled reforms and bureaucratic inaction have put India in its tightest spot since early 1991, when the country neared bankruptcy. That has led to a new creed within the white-collar community: Progress can no longer be appropriated privately.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe cannot continue to be concerned only about our businesses when the system at large is failing,â said Anupa Sahney, 46, who runs a financial consulting company. âIt is high time that the educated and affluent do something outside drawing room conversations.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Among India First members is a growing sense that despite their wealth, they are losing out to more politically connected groups.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWith what has come to pass in politics with minority blocs and reservations, weâve reached a stage where if you are affluent, and not a minority, youâre being discriminated against,â Ms. Sahney said. âOur kids donât get into medical schools because you need 99.8 percent.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Though the group, which was formed eight months ago, has 50,000 registered members, it has only 250 who are actively campaigning. The meet-and-greet with Mr. Sawant and the power walkers is part of India Firstâs efforts to introduce the candidate to other affluent people in the places they frequent: parks, homes, luxury hotels. An India First adviser to Mr. Sawant said she urged him to master a firm handshake and to avoid speaking in English, in which he was not fluent, unless required.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">India First has also conducted door-to-door voter registration drives in glass-paneled towers, began a video campaign with testimonies supporting Mr. Modi, and hosted interactive sessions with prominent speakers like the national treasurer of the B.J.P., Piyush Goyal, the spiritual leader Sri Sri Ravi Shankar, and the economist-turned-politician Subramanian Swamy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Because India First is not a registered organization, members took turns to pick up the tab.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe would have never discussed Indian politics in the menâs room at the Willingdon Club,â said Ankit Somani, 28, who runs an IT solutions company, referring to a private club where the old-moneyed sit in cane chairs and watch people play golf. âBut the truth is that affluent people want to be politically engaged. All they lack is an enabling environment.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the 2009 parliamentary elections, only 43.3 percent of the voters turned up at polling booths in south Mumbai. Six months before the polls, gunmen had stormed two luxury hotels and a railway station, killing 168 people, which led to public outrage over governance and security, but that did not translate into voter turnout.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe always sit and crib, âThis is wrong with the country, that is wrong with the country,â â said Mr. Somani, sitting over a serving of sushi in Fenix, one of the restaurants devastated during the 2008 terror attacks. âBut somewhere you realize that if you donât go out and do something, you lose the right to crib.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">According to Rahul Mehra, 29, who runs businesses in the hospitality sector, 2014 is an election of economics.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBill Clinton defeated sitting President George H.W. Bush with his campaign, âItâs the economy, stupid,â â he said. âSomething similar is about to happen here.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When the conversation about India First began in a living room, the aim was to âchannel restless energy,â said Mr. Mehra.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe didnât come together as some sort of Modi-nama,â said Ms. Sahney, the financial consultant. âBut we happened to be on the same page: This country needs a good C.E.O., and in 2014, that person is Narendra Modi.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The members of India First know very well that their choice of candidate comes with controversy. As the chief minister of Gujarat, a state on India&#8217;s northwest coast, Mr. Modi has been dogged by allegations that he did nothing to stop deadly riots between Hindus and Muslims in Gujarat in 2002 after a Muslim mob attacked a train full of Hindu pilgrims in Godhra and a fire broke out, killing 59 Hindus.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe question of Godhra looms over everybody,â said Mr. Somani. âIt was something that scared me, something I cannot condone. I felt the need to go back and find out what exactly happened there.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The group put out a research paper that outlined the facts in the 2002 Gujarat riots and listed other outbreaks of religious violence in the country since 1946, but did not offer any opinion on Mr. Modi</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThis man took office two months before the incident, after 65 years of a communally charged atmosphere,â said Mr. Jalan, the entrepreneur. âI donât think even Superman could have stopped that. The question is did he abet it? The answer is no. It came from the Supreme Court.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At Priyadarshini Park, the stock brokers were more concerned about the economy than about religion, asking Mr. Sawant questions about how he would support Mr. Modiâs economic agenda for the country and what the city could expect from him. Mr. Sawant had answers to some questions, and generous laughter for others.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âTo match up with Modi, you will have to do a lot of work,â an amiable and elderly morning walker offered. âBut we are with you for now.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><i></i><i>Mansi Choksi is a journalist based in Mumbai. You can follow her on Twitter <a href="https://www.twitter.com/mansi_choksi">@mansi_choksi</a>.</i></p>
